1
0:00:32,370 --> 0:00:33,880
南极洲
Antarctica.

2
0:00:37,360 --> 0:00:42,960
地球上最冷 最恶劣 最偏远的大陆
The coldest, the harshest and the most remote continent on Earth.

3
0:00:49,600 --> 0:00:54,920
曾几何时 人类从未涉足这片净土
No human being has ever descended into the depths that surround it...

4
0:00:57,900 --> 0:00:59,380
直到如今
..Until now.

5
0:01:06,600 --> 0:01:11,160
探索深海 和探索太空一样具有挑战性
The deep ocean is as challenging to explore as space.

6
0:01:14,320 --> 0:01:16,920
对于人类而言 海洋的最深处
We know more about the surface of Mars

7
0:01:16,970 --> 0:01:19,840
比火星的表面更神秘莫测
than we do about the deepest parts of our seas.

8
0:01:43,520 --> 0:01:47,160
如今我们可以潜入这些未知的深处
Now we can dive these uncharted depths

9
0:01:47,240 --> 0:01:49,740
去探索面纱下的秘密
 to discover what secrets lie beneath.

10
0:02:24,720 --> 0:02:29,120
沿着冰山墙面不断下潜
Sinking down beside the submerged wall of an iceberg,

11
0:02:29,120 --> 0:02:31,560
我们进入了一个残酷的世界
we enter an unforgiving world.

12
0:02:41,800 --> 0:02:44,960
这里的水是地球最冰冷的
These waters are the coldest on Earth.

13
0:02:49,600 --> 0:02:54,400
随着下潜深度的增加 压强也愈加紧迫
As we descend into the deep, the pressure increases relentlessly.

14
0:03:11,880 --> 0:03:14,920
来自海面上的光也逐渐消失
And the light from above all but disappears.

15
0:03:22,360 --> 0:03:24,200
但不可思议的是
Yet, incredibly...

16
0:03:27,800 --> 0:03:29,640
这里有生命存在
..There is life here.

17
0:03:51,320 --> 0:03:55,730
我们曾认为 在极地海洋的深处
We might have expected that, deep beneath the surface of the polar seas,

18
0:03:56,840 --> 0:03:59,400
应该是一片不毛之地
the waters would be truly barren.

19
0:04:07,120 --> 0:04:11,760
但事实上 我们在这儿发现的生物多到令人难以想象
But in fact we find life here in unimaginable abundance.

20
0:04:25,920 --> 0:04:30,160
丰裕多样的物种也不仅仅出现在南极水域
Nor is such great abundance confined to Antarctic waters.

21
0:04:33,520 --> 0:04:39,970
洋流将世界各大海域的物种资源带向了深渊
Currents carry this richness into the depths of almost every ocean around the world.

22
0:04:43,700 --> 0:04:46,080
令人惊讶的是 海洋深处
Astonishingly, in the deep sea,

23
0:04:46,080 --> 0:04:49,760
藏匿着地球上最繁多的生命
there is more life than anywhere else on Earth.

24
0:05:17,200 --> 0:05:21,080
阳光褪散 黑暗笼罩
The sunlight fades and the seas darken.

25
0:05:25,000 --> 0:05:27,800
这是太平洋 200米的深处
Here in the Pacific, 200 metres down,

26
0:05:27,800 --> 0:05:30,800
一个陌生的世界
we enter an alien world.

27
0:05:33,460 --> 0:05:35,040
这里是暮光区
The Twilight Zone

28
0:05:35,940 --> 0:05:38,330
永远处于昏暗的海域
a sea of eternal gloom.

29
0:05:46,360 --> 0:05:48,440
这里遍布神奇的生物
There are strange creatures here.

30
0:05:50,120 --> 0:05:52,410
这是一只火体虫
A pyrosome.

31
0:05:52,640 --> 0:05:54,960
像一管两米长的大果冻
A tube of jelly two metres

32
0:05:54,960 --> 0:05:58,440
游在上面的白鳍鲨与它相比
long that dwarfs a visitor from above -

33
0:05:58,440 --> 0:06:00,480
像个小矮子
an oceanic whitetip shark.

34
0:06:09,320 --> 0:06:13,290
经过层层过滤 只有极少量的光线 照射在这片深海处
Only a tiny amount of light filters down this far.

35
0:06:17,880 --> 0:06:22,690
要想在这里生存 就必须充分利用每一丝光线
Survival here means making the most of every last glimmer.

36
0:06:32,040 --> 0:06:33,580
这儿有条剑鱼
A swordfish.

37
0:06:42,240 --> 0:06:44,680
它的眼睛像网球一样大
Its eyes are as big as tennis balls,

38
0:06:44,680 --> 0:06:47,620
以便在这永恒昏暗中保持视力
to help it see in the perpetual dusk.

39
0:06:52,920 --> 0:06:54,240
这是一只乌贼
A squid,

40
0:06:54,240 --> 0:06:56,560
这种乌贼只在这里生活
but this is one that lives only here.

41
0:06:58,080 --> 0:07:00,760
它的右眼看起来是永久向下的
Its right eye looks permanently downwards.

42
0:07:03,400 --> 0:07:07,040
但它的左眼要大得多 并且被训练的能向上看
But its left eye is much bigger and trained upwards to detect the

43
0:07:07,040 --> 0:07:10,320
这样就能探测到附近水域中猎物的轮廓
silhouettes of prey swimming nearer the surface.

44
0:07:12,880 --> 0:07:16,000
难怪它被称为 斜眼乌贼
No wonder it's nicknamed "The cockeyed squid".

45
0:07:22,360 --> 0:07:24,000
还有更神奇的
And even stranger.

46
0:07:26,560 --> 0:07:28,480
这是管眼鱼
This is barreleye...

47
0:07:31,560 --> 0:07:35,000
它有着一颗透明的脑袋
..A fish with a transparent head

48
0:07:35,000 --> 0:07:39,720
里面满是胶状物 因此可以透过头部组织看到头骨
filled with jelly so that it can look up through its skull.

49
0:07:56,960 --> 0:08:05,020
难以置信的是 这片暮光区 是海洋中90%鱼类的避难所
We now know that the Twilight Zone is a refuge for an incredible 90% of all fish in the ocean.

50
0:08:10,880 --> 0:08:12,050
只有在晚上
Only at night

51
0:08:12,080 --> 0:08:16,440
大量灯鱼才迁往海面
do vast shoals of lanternfish migrate to the surface

52
0:08:16,580 --> 0:08:18,580
捕食微小的浮游生物
to feed on tiny plankton.

53
0:08:29,640 --> 0:08:32,400
白天 它们就撤回于此
By day, they retreat back down here.

54
0:08:48,360 --> 0:08:49,920
美洲大赤鱿
Humboldt squid.

55
0:09:02,640 --> 0:09:05,520
身长两米 重达50千克
Two metres long and 50 kilos in weight.

56
0:09:10,800 --> 0:09:13,920
像大多数鱿鱼一样 它们是贪婪的猎手
Like most squid, they're voracious hunters.

57
0:09:21,480 --> 0:09:23,120
数量成百上千
There are hundreds of them.

58
0:09:34,440 --> 0:09:36,760
它们发现了一群隐藏在
They've found a shoal of lanternfish,

59
0:09:36,760 --> 0:09:40,120
南美洲海岸 水下800米处的灯鱼
hiding 800 metres down, off the coast of South America.

60
0:09:53,160 --> 0:09:55,840
它们的触手上武装着强大的吸盘
Their tentacles are armed with powerful suckers

61
0:09:55,840 --> 0:09:57,760
可以抓住猎物
with which they grab their prey.

62
0:10:14,160 --> 0:10:16,760
若没有更多的灯鱼供它们捕获
And when there are no more lanternfish to be found...

63
0:10:19,240 --> 0:10:21,480
它们便自相残杀
..They turn on each other.

64
0:10:32,360 --> 0:10:35,800
这只鱿鱼捕获了一只小鱿鱼藏于触手中
This squid has caught a smaller one in its tentacles.

65
0:10:40,720 --> 0:10:42,920
为了掩饰以得到片刻休憩
To hide its capture from the rest,

66
0:10:42,920 --> 0:10:45,280
它会释放像烟幕一样的墨汁
it releases a smokescreen of black ink.

67
0:10:58,200 --> 0:11:00,880
但一只更大的赤鱿挑衅
But then an even bigger one challenges it...

68
0:11:07,800 --> 0:11:09,640
并偷走了它的的猎物
..And steals its catch.

69
0:11:18,880 --> 0:11:20,220
暮光区
The Twilight Zone

70
0:11:20,250 --> 0:11:23,160
是美洲大赤鱿最喜欢的猎场
is the Humboldt squid's favoured hunting ground.

71
0:11:25,010 --> 0:11:26,660
他们很少深入到
They seldom go deeper...

72
0:11:28,040 --> 0:11:31,200
下面的永恒黑暗水域
..Into the world of perpetual blackness below...

73
0:11:36,520 --> 0:11:38,280
午夜区
..The Midnight Zone.

74
0:11:49,160 --> 0:11:53,640
这是总水深三分之二处 阳光却步之地
Two thirds of a mile from the surface, beyond the reach the sun.

75
0:11:59,440 --> 0:12:01,720
这暗无天日的水域
A giant black void,

76
0:12:01,720 --> 0:12:05,720
比世界上所有栖息地的总和都大
larger than all the rest of the world's habitats combined.

77
0:12:10,800 --> 0:12:12,320
这里的生物
There's life here...

78
0:12:13,960 --> 0:12:15,800
非比寻常
..But not as we know it.

79
0:12:26,720 --> 0:12:30,680
它们像外星人一样发出耀眼的光
Alien-like creatures produce dazzling displays of light.

80
0:12:43,680 --> 0:12:48,120
几乎所有动物都需要吸引配偶并击退捕食者
Nearly all animals need to attract mates and repel predators.

81
0:12:51,040 --> 0:12:55,320
这种光的语言在这里非常普遍
This language of light is so widespread here that these signals

82
0:12:55,320 --> 0:12:59,000
这些信号可能是整个星球上
are probably the commonest form of communication

83
0:12:59,000 --> 0:13:01,560
最常见的通讯形式
on the entire planet.

84
0:13:03,010 --> 0:13:05,900
但我们对它们仍然所知甚少
And yet we still know little about them.

85
0:13:29,960 --> 0:13:31,660
猎手们照亮自己
Hunters illuminate themselves,

86
0:13:31,660 --> 0:13:35,200
以此吸引好奇的猎物
and by doing so attract inquisitive prey.

87
0:13:47,720 --> 0:13:49,760
这是尖牙鱼
This is fangtooth.

88
0:13:51,840 --> 0:13:55,560
它有着同体形鱼类中最大的牙齿
It has the largest teeth for its size of any fish.

89
0:13:58,320 --> 0:13:59,870
尖牙鱼的头部和身体
There are pressure sensors

90
0:13:59,870 --> 0:14:02,440
都具有压力传感器 以此探测
all over its head and body which can detect

91
0:14:02,440 --> 0:14:04,840
周围游动的任何事物
anything moving in the surrounding water.

92
0:14:11,600 --> 0:14:15,000
这是午夜区中最贪婪的鱼
It's the Midnight Zone's most voracious fish.

93
0:14:17,160 --> 0:14:20,120
但猎物可以用光来分散其注意力
But prey use light as a distraction.

94
0:14:25,000 --> 0:14:27,440
发光的墨水也可作为诱饵
A decoy of luminous ink.

95
0:14:36,920 --> 0:14:39,120
在这片 漆黑深海中
Down here, in this blackness...

96
0:14:41,200 --> 0:14:44,520
生物已摆脱时间的束缚
..Creatures live beyond the normal rules of time.

97
0:14:51,440 --> 0:14:55,000
管水母群是永生不朽的
Siphonophores are virtually eternal.

98
0:14:55,000 --> 0:14:57,400
它们不断地克隆自己
They repeatedly clone themselves...

99
0:14:58,840 --> 0:15:02,280
有些群体最终长得比蓝鲸还长
..Some eventually growing longer than a blue whale.

100
0:15:26,560 --> 0:15:29,080
这里像下雪一样
Down here it snows.

101
0:15:37,680 --> 0:15:40,680
连续不断的有机碎片云
Continuous clouds of organic debris

102
0:15:40,680 --> 0:15:43,120
从上面缓缓飘下
drift slowly down from above.

103
0:15:50,240 --> 0:15:53,640
这是食物 所有滤食性动物
This is food, and a whole variety

104
0:15:53,640 --> 0:15:56,360
都靠捕食它生存
of filter feeders depend on it.

105
0:15:59,760 --> 0:16:01,120
水母
Jellyfish...

106
0:16:09,400 --> 0:16:11,960
还有纤弱的海参
..And delicate sea cucumbers.

107
0:16:31,000 --> 0:16:34,360
他们错过的1%的海洋雪
The 1% of marine snow they miss

108
0:16:34,360 --> 0:16:36,640
最终落定海底
eventually settles on the sea floor.

109
0:17:04,680 --> 0:17:10,900
经过几百万年的沉积 逐渐形成了一层厚厚的淤泥
Over millions of years it forms a layer of mud up to a mile thick.

110
0:17:15,120 --> 0:17:17,440
这是一片空旷的平原
It's an empty plain that covers

111
0:17:17,440 --> 0:17:19,760
覆盖了地球表面的一半
half the surface of our planet.

112
0:17:45,720 --> 0:17:49,840
深海海床最初可能死气沉沉
The deep sea bed may at first appear lifeless...

113
0:17:52,080 --> 0:17:56,240
但一种在泥浆中生活的独特生物 以此为家
..But it's home to a unique cast of mud-dwellers.

114
0:17:59,160 --> 0:18:01,650
海蛤蟆
The sea toad.

115
0:18:03,440 --> 0:18:07,440
一种有着巨大嘴巴和无比耐心的
It is an ambush predator with an enormous mouth...

116
0:18:09,160 --> 0:18:11,120
伏击捕食者
..And infinite patience.

117
0:18:21,800 --> 0:18:24,880
这种鱼在这里生活了太久
This fish has been living for so long here

118
0:18:24,880 --> 0:18:26,640
连它的鳍都发生了变化
that its fins have changed

119
0:18:26,640 --> 0:18:28,440
进化成了更实用的部位
into something more useful.

120
0:18:34,440 --> 0:18:36,240
脚
Feet.

121
0:18:40,800 --> 0:18:43,800
助它在海底行走移动
They help it shuffle about on the sea floor.

122
0:19:04,080 --> 0:19:07,340
这是烙饼章鱼
The flapjack octopus.

123
0:19:11,280 --> 0:19:13,930
它在淤泥上缓缓起舞
It hovers just above the surface of the mud

124
0:19:13,940 --> 0:19:18,010
优雅从容地筛选虫子
as it delicately sifts through it, searching for worms.

125
0:19:21,280 --> 0:19:24,720
但危险来临的瞬间 它也能如火箭般迅速躲闪
But it can jet away at the first sign of danger.

126
0:19:43,720 --> 0:19:46,880
灰六鳃鲨和大白鲨一样大
A sixgill shark as big as a great white.

127
0:19:48,400 --> 0:19:51,600
它可以整整一年不吃食物
It may not have eaten for an entire year.

128
0:19:58,240 --> 0:20:00,200
它耗费最小的能量
It patrols the mud plains

129
0:20:00,200 --> 0:20:02,840
在泥面平原上巡逻
using a minimum amount of energy.

130
0:20:16,640 --> 0:20:19,440
上面 一具庞大的抹香鲸尸体
High above, the carcass of a huge

131
0:20:19,440 --> 0:20:22,240
正在慢慢腐烂
sperm whale is slowly decaying.

132
0:20:28,920 --> 0:20:31,960
这将是深海生物的财富
This will be a bonanza for the creatures of the deep.

133
0:20:33,200 --> 0:20:36,280
整整30吨的食物
Food, 30 tonnes of it.

134
0:20:49,520 --> 0:20:53,040
最终鲸落海底
Finally, it settles on the ocean floor...

135
0:20:55,080 --> 0:20:57,560
它的存在很快被发现
..And its presence is soon detected.

136
0:21:07,360 --> 0:21:12,200
灰六鳃鲨有异常敏锐的嗅觉
Sixgill sharks have an exceptionally acute sense of smell.

137
0:21:16,800 --> 0:21:20,640
仅在鲸落地的25分钟后
Just 25 minutes after the whale's carcass arrives...

138
0:21:22,800 --> 0:21:24,680
一条灰六腮鲨就发现了它
..A sixgill finds it.

139
0:21:45,920 --> 0:21:49,160
每一口撕咬 都释放出血液 扩散开来
Each bite releases blood into the current.

140
0:22:30,560 --> 0:22:33,760
此地有食物的消息迅速传播
The news that food is here spreads quickly.

141
0:22:42,040 --> 0:22:45,360
两条更贪婪的灰六腮鲨到达
Two more ravenous sixgills arrive.

142
0:22:54,120 --> 0:22:55,720
12小时内
Within 12 hours,

143
0:22:55,720 --> 0:22:57,640
有七条巨鲨寻味前来
there are seven enormous sharks

144
0:22:57,640 --> 0:23:01,520
它们互相推搡 争抢夺食
jostling with one another as they compete to tear off mouthfuls.

145
0:23:13,840 --> 0:23:16,200
无人甘愿退让
No-one is prepared to back off.

146
0:23:59,600 --> 0:24:03,720
24小时后 尸体的三分之一已被吃干抹净
24 hours later and a third of the carcass has gone.

147
0:24:35,360 --> 0:24:39,280
第一条鲨鱼狼吞虎咽 势要饱餐一顿
The first arrival has gorged until it's completely full.

148
0:24:44,400 --> 0:24:49,480
这顿饭足够维持它一整年
This single meal may be enough to sustain it for a whole year.

149
0:24:55,960 --> 0:24:58,960
现在清理队到达了
Now the clean-up team arrives.

150
0:25:02,200 --> 0:25:05,880
蜘蛛蟹的后肢钳着珊瑚
Spider crabs carrying coral in their hind legs,

151
0:25:05,880 --> 0:25:08,800
大概以此伪装 从而免遭攻击
presumably as makeshift body armour.

152
0:25:17,040 --> 0:25:18,760
这里也有石蟹
There are rock crabs here, too.

153
0:25:21,680 --> 0:25:23,000
它们发现尸体的速度
They probably detected

154
0:25:23,000 --> 0:25:25,600
可能和鲨鱼齐平
the carcass almost as soon as the sharks...

155
0:25:27,320 --> 0:25:29,160
但它们行动缓慢
..But they can't move as fast.

156
0:25:33,840 --> 0:25:37,180
一个月后 30多种食腐动物
A month on, and over 30 species of scavenger

157
0:25:37,210 --> 0:25:40,490
正在瓜分最后的残羹剩饭
are clearing away the last edible fragments.

158
0:25:42,920 --> 0:25:46,840
但现在它们也吸引了掠食者
But now the scavengers are attracting their own predators.

159
0:25:53,240 --> 0:25:56,440
叉尾带鱼 习惯直立游泳
Scabbardfish, habitually swimming upright,

160
0:25:56,440 --> 0:25:58,200
正一个个摘食它们
are picking them off one by one.

161
0:26:19,520 --> 0:26:22,060
鲸鱼的牙齿开始脱落 
Some of the whale's teeth have been dislodged

162
0:26:22,170 --> 0:26:24,880
骨骼也开始散架
as the skeleton starts to fall apart.

163
0:26:28,120 --> 0:26:32,720
四个月后 这里只剩下森森白骨
Four months later, there is nothing left but a few bones.

164
0:26:40,440 --> 0:26:43,340
即便如此 这对某些生物来说
But even they are food...

165
0:26:46,360 --> 0:26:47,720
也还是食物
..For something.

166
0:26:54,640 --> 0:26:56,320
僵尸蠕虫
Zombie worms.

167
0:27:00,240 --> 0:27:03,680
它们通过注射酸性物质 在尸骨钻孔
They tunnel into the bones by injecting acid...

168
0:27:04,680 --> 0:27:08,560
从而获取遗留在骨中的少量脂肪
..And so reach the tiny amounts of fat that still remain there.

169
0:27:10,960 --> 0:27:12,560
这可能需要几十年
It may take decades,

170
0:27:12,600 --> 0:27:16,480
但最终骨头将变为碎屑
but eventually the last of the bones will crumble

171
0:27:16,480 --> 0:27:18,960
整个30吨重的尸体
and the whole 30-tonne carcass

172
0:27:18,960 --> 0:27:21,000
将被完全回收利用
will have been recycled.

173
0:27:28,200 --> 0:27:29,410
这条鲸的陨落 
A whale fall

174
0:27:29,450 --> 0:27:33,400
是这片海底沙漠中短暂的绿洲
is a temporary oasis in the desert of the sea floor.

175
0:27:36,800 --> 0:27:39,280
但这里也有永恒的绿洲
But there are permanent oases here, too.

176
0:27:53,440 --> 0:27:56,080
泥上突出的岩石
Rocks projecting above the mud

177
0:27:56,080 --> 0:27:59,040
为深海珊瑚的生长提供了场所
provide anchorage for deep-sea corals.

178
0:28:17,480 --> 0:28:21,000
3.5英里深的水下
As far down as 3.5 miles,

179
0:28:21,000 --> 0:28:24,200
深海中的珊瑚种类
there are more species of coral in the deep

180
0:28:24,200 --> 0:28:26,720
比热带浅礁处的多
than on shallow tropical reefs.

181
0:28:35,160 --> 0:28:36,690
没有阳光
Without sunlight,

182
0:28:36,800 --> 0:28:40,540
他们只能依靠漂浮的食物存活
they rely solely on food drifting in the current.

183
0:28:43,920 --> 0:28:48,560
一根纤毛需要一年的时间来生长
And they grow just a hair's breadth a year.

184
0:28:54,280 --> 0:28:57,920
但其中一些可以活4000年
But some of them can live for 4,000 years.

185
0:29:04,640 --> 0:29:08,000
就像它们的浅水亲属一样
They, like their shallow water relatives,

186
0:29:08,000 --> 0:29:10,920
它们为其他生物提供家园
provide homes for all kinds of other creatures.

187
0:29:36,480 --> 0:29:41,040
最美丽的海绵动物 就生长在珊瑚中间
Growing among the corals is one of the most beautiful of sponges.

188
0:29:44,760 --> 0:29:48,080
这是维纳斯花篮
This is Venus' flower basket.

189
0:29:55,760 --> 0:29:57,600
这些海绵生物有它们的房客
These sponges have lodgers.

190
0:29:58,840 --> 0:30:00,600
俪虾
Shrimps.

191
0:30:08,480 --> 0:30:10,960
礁石上捕食者虎视眈眈
There are plenty of predators on the reef,

192
0:30:10,960 --> 0:30:12,800
所以这些俪虾很幸运
so the shrimps are fortunate.

193
0:30:17,400 --> 0:30:19,260
当它们还在幼虫时期
Both this male and female

194
0:30:19,420 --> 0:30:22,760
一雌一雄就被卷进海绵洞中
were swept into this sponge when they were tiny larvae,

195
0:30:22,760 --> 0:30:25,330
海绵洞中的污物
along with the minute particles of food

196
0:30:25,450 --> 0:30:27,260
便是它们的食物
on which the sponge feeds.

197
0:30:31,400 --> 0:30:35,130
它们执子之手 与子偕老
They found each other and have been here ever since.

198
0:30:50,040 --> 0:30:51,880
如今俪虾都长大了
Now they're full-grown

199
0:30:51,880 --> 0:30:54,360
雌性俪虾也产卵了
and the female is carrying eggs.

200
0:31:07,480 --> 0:31:08,940
一旦孵化出来
Once hatched, the larvae

201
0:31:08,940 --> 0:31:11,440
幼虫就会从海绵的壁上游出来
will swim out through the sponge's walls.

202
0:31:17,800 --> 0:31:20,240
但这对成年虾却不会迁移
But the shrimps will never leave.

203
0:31:21,600 --> 0:31:23,120
它们出不来
They can't.

204
0:31:29,360 --> 0:31:33,240
它们现在体形太大了 无法抽身离开
They are now far too big to go out the way they came in,

205
0:31:33,690 --> 0:31:36,600
毫无疑问 它们在这里要比在礁石上
and no doubt they will live longer here than they would

206
0:31:36,600 --> 0:31:40,480
四处游荡且无所庇护 活的更久
if they were wandering about on the reef unprotected.

207
0:31:53,280 --> 0:31:57,760
不过 海绵这种简单的动物
But how one of the simplest of all animals, a sponge,

208
0:31:57,760 --> 0:32:01,280
是如何建造出这样一个复杂的结构
is able to build such a complex structure,

209
0:32:01,280 --> 0:32:03,480
为俪虾创造良好的生存环境
to the great benefit of the shrimps...

210
0:32:04,880 --> 0:32:07,120
是一个谜
..Is a mystery...

211
0:32:07,120 --> 0:32:09,240
更是一个奇迹
..And surely a marvel.

212
0:32:26,200 --> 0:32:30,800
但如今 它们曾经无忧无虑的世界被夷为平地
But today their timeless world is being reduced to rubble.

213
0:32:39,080 --> 0:32:43,360
人类的过度捕捞清空了上层水域
As overfishing empties the surface waters of the seas,

214
0:32:43,360 --> 0:32:47,000
渔民的网开始伸向更深的水域
trawlers have started to ransack the deep.

215
0:32:50,440 --> 0:32:53,160
数不尽的珊瑚礁
Now countless numbers of the reefs

216
0:32:53,160 --> 0:32:55,560
在数千年的繁荣后
that have flourished here for millennia

217
0:32:55,560 --> 0:32:57,400
毁于旦夕
lie in ruins.

218
0:33:27,240 --> 0:33:31,720
随着时间的推移 海底的有机质慢慢分解
Over time, organic matter on the sea floor slowly decays...

219
0:33:32,760 --> 0:33:34,280
释放出甲烷
..Producing methane.

220
0:34:35,760 --> 0:34:37,720
在墨西哥湾
In the Gulf of Mexico

221
0:34:37,720 --> 0:34:41,600
这些海底有机质会形成超咸液体
these eruptions also release a super-salty liquid.

222
0:34:49,600 --> 0:34:51,200
浓盐水
Brine.

223
0:35:02,120 --> 0:35:05,240
它们的盐度比普通海水浓上5倍
Five times heavier than seawater,

224
0:35:05,240 --> 0:35:08,560
在海底积聚成一个个盐湖
it accumulates in great pools on the sea floor.

225
0:35:14,360 --> 0:35:16,840
难以想象这样的画面
It's difficult to make sense of the sight.

226
0:35:24,160 --> 0:35:29,160
在海底深处 遍布15米深的
A lake of concentrated saltwater, 15 metres deep

227
0:35:30,050 --> 0:35:31,890
高浓度盐湖
at the bottom of the sea.

228
0:35:39,600 --> 0:35:43,000
更奇怪的是 在这些咸水湖边
Around its margin, perhaps even more strangely,

229
0:35:43,000 --> 0:35:45,640
居然有着繁茂的生物群
there is a profusion of life.

230
0:35:52,640 --> 0:35:56,560
巨型贻贝 一种可以存活上百年的生物
Giant mussels, that can live and grow for a century or more,

231
0:35:56,890 --> 0:35:58,640
在盐湖边密密麻麻的生长
pack tightly together,

232
0:35:58,640 --> 0:36:02,360
周围还簇拥着以贻贝为食的俪虾和蹲龙虾
dwarfing the shrimps and squat lobsters that feed around them.

233
0:36:31,160 --> 0:36:34,200
凶狠的食腐动物 海鳗
Cutthroat eels, scavengers,

234
0:36:34,200 --> 0:36:35,710
也来到盐湖边
come to the shores of the

235
0:36:35,710 --> 0:36:38,200
寻找口粮
brine lake in search of something edible.

236
0:36:47,000 --> 0:36:49,960
有些海鳗甚至涉险进入到盐湖中
Some even venture into the brine.

237
0:37:23,440 --> 0:37:25,280
在盐湖中待得太久
Spending too long in it

238
0:37:25,280 --> 0:37:27,880
会让海鳗中毒性休克
can send an eel into toxic shock.

239
0:37:39,720 --> 0:37:42,360
它只有期望尽快浮出盐湖
Its only hope is to rise above it.

240
0:37:57,160 --> 0:37:58,800
这只海鳗成功逃脱了
It manages to escape.

241
0:38:07,960 --> 0:38:09,640
而大多数动物则没有那么幸运
Others are not so lucky.

242
0:38:17,040 --> 0:38:19,360
高浓度盐水腐蚀了他们的身体
The brine embalms their bodies...

243
0:38:21,160 --> 0:38:23,760
盐湖边堆积着长时间以来
..And the casualties of decades

244
0:38:23,760 --> 0:38:26,160
殉难的动物尸体
accumulate around the margins.

245
0:38:46,160 --> 0:38:49,600
但洋底深处更为凶险
But parts of the deep are even more hostile.

246
0:38:57,200 --> 0:39:03,300
纵横于此的 是离洋底数英里深的巨型裂缝
In places, gigantic cracks stretch for many miles across the ocean floor...

247
0:39:18,160 --> 0:39:21,920
这些巨大峡谷直逼地心深处
..Canyons that plunge towards the centre of the Earth.

248
0:39:29,360 --> 0:39:31,190
勘探船带回的扫描图像
Scans from survey vessels

249
0:39:31,190 --> 0:39:34,360
为人们形象地重现
make it possible to graphically reconstruct

250
0:39:34,360 --> 0:39:37,400
这一巨幅海底景观
an image of this vast submarine landscape.

251
0:39:45,240 --> 0:39:48,400
位于太平洋的马里亚纳海沟 距离海底7英里
The deepest of all, at almost seven miles,

252
0:39:48,400 --> 0:39:51,240
是迄今发现的最深的海沟
is the Mariana Trench in the Pacific Ocean.

253
0:39:57,200 --> 0:40:00,560
即使珠穆拉玛峰都会隐没其中
Even Mount Everest could disappear inside it.

254
0:40:15,760 --> 0:40:19,080
在这些海底峡谷
Down here, in these deep ravines,

255
0:40:19,080 --> 0:40:23,080
人们曾经认为不可能有生命迹象
it was once thought that nothing whatever could possibly survive.

256
0:40:30,240 --> 0:40:32,800
但事实证明即使是这里也有生物存在
But there is life even here...

257
0:40:39,640 --> 0:40:41,200
海蛞蝓
..A kind of sea slug.

258
0:40:48,880 --> 0:40:51,210
还有被戏称为 大洋猪 的动物
A so-called "Sea pig".

259
0:40:53,000 --> 0:40:57,200
这些简单的生物以漂降到此的
They, and other simple creatures, manage to survive on the

260
0:40:57,200 --> 0:41:00,680
极少数食物为食
minuscule amount of food that drifts down here.

261
0:41:04,120 --> 0:41:05,840
与这只海星类似
Like this starfish,

262
0:41:05,840 --> 0:41:07,170
它们可以承受住
they can withstand pressure

263
0:41:07,170 --> 0:41:11,960
相当于50架巨型喷气机的压力
equivalent of 50 jumbo jets stacked on top of one another.

264
0:41:33,200 --> 0:41:35,560
远程针式探头
A remote camera probe reveals

265
0:41:35,560 --> 0:41:38,240
揭示出这些不可思议的发现
the most extraordinary discovery of all...

266
0:41:45,760 --> 0:41:48,760
幽灵般的狮子鱼
..The ethereal snailfish.

267
0:41:52,640 --> 0:41:54,800
距海底5英里深的峡谷里
At five miles down,

268
0:41:54,800 --> 0:41:58,440
狮子鱼是迄今被发现的唯一鱼类
this is the deepest living fish so far discovered.

269
0:42:04,720 --> 0:42:07,520
没想到狮子鱼这样
No-one imagined that an animal as

270
0:42:07,520 --> 0:42:09,060
结构复杂的动物
complex as a fish

271
0:42:09,180 --> 0:42:12,200
也可以在这样恶劣的环境下生存
 could existin such extreme pressures.

272
0:42:24,400 --> 0:42:28,920
从暮光区深入到午夜区
From the greatest depths to the uppermost limit of the Twilight Zone,

273
0:42:29,010 --> 0:42:32,280
生活着的各式生物 似乎深海中并没有
it seems that there is nowhere in the deep sea

274
0:42:32,320 --> 0:42:35,080
人们以为的死亡地带
where life of some kind can't survive.

275
0:42:39,920 --> 0:42:42,800
于是人们开始认为地球上最早的生命
And we now think that the deep sea may well be

276
0:42:42,800 --> 0:42:44,600
很可能起源于深海
where life on Earth began.

277
0:42:58,480 --> 0:43:04,300
世界上地质特征最为丰富的海底深处
Here, in a world hidden within the greatest geological feature on Earth...

278
0:43:07,620 --> 0:43:10,920
地球海洋的中央 隐藏着一座
..Running right down the middle of the world's oceans,

279
0:43:10,920 --> 0:43:15,640
延绵横跨整个地球的水下山脉
an underwater mountain range, spanning the entire globe.

280
0:43:20,760 --> 0:43:22,480
大洋中脊
The Mid-Ocean Ridge.

281
0:43:36,640 --> 0:43:38,440
在南太平洋
In the South Pacific,

282
0:43:38,440 --> 0:43:41,080
海底频受地质灾害
the ocean floor is being torn apart.

283
0:44:53,520 --> 0:44:56,520
地球上超过四分之三的火山
Over three quarters of the planet's volcanic activity

284
0:44:56,520 --> 0:44:58,320
在海底爆发
occurs in the deep...

285
0:45:05,680 --> 0:45:09,280
而几乎所有的海底火山都分布在大洋中脊两侧
..Almost all of it along the Mid-Ocean Ridge.

286
0:45:13,280 --> 0:45:17,720
伴随剧烈的地壳运动而来的是丰富的天然资源
But from this titanic violence come great riches.

287
0:45:26,960 --> 0:45:30,480
浓烟和滚烫的海水从海底缝隙中涌出
Gases and scalding water gush up through the crevices.

288
0:45:39,840 --> 0:45:44,040
凝结成大量矿物质 状如烟囱
Minerals condensing from these jets build up great chimneys...

289
0:45:45,760 --> 0:45:47,440
谓之深海喷泉
hydrothermal vents.

290
0:45:51,360 --> 0:45:55,620
就像这个被称为 哥斯拉 的30米高喷泉
This one, 30 metres tall, has been named Godzilla.

291
0:46:03,660 --> 0:46:05,700
我们震惊地发现哥斯拉
Astonishingly, we now know

292
0:46:05,700 --> 0:46:10,380
拥有着跟热带雨林一样繁杂的生物群
that they hold as much life as tropical rainforests.

293
0:46:17,500 --> 0:46:21,380
甚至有些地方 一小平方米
In places, half a million individual animals

294
0:46:21,380 --> 0:46:24,460
就能聚集数十万的各式生物
are crammed into a single square metre.

295
0:46:37,300 --> 0:46:41,050
这些生物完全依靠微生物生存
They depend entirely for their food on bacteria.

296
0:46:43,340 --> 0:46:48,280
而微生物便以溶解在热浪中的化学物质为食
And THEY feed on chemicals dissolved in the searingly hot fluid.

297
0:46:55,120 --> 0:47:00,240
螃蟹会吃掉覆盖在它们壳上的细菌群
Crabs consume the bacterial mats that coat their shells.

298
0:47:14,080 --> 0:47:16,920
有些动物则让这些菌群
Others maintain bacterial cultures

299
0:47:16,920 --> 0:47:19,320
寄居在他们的身体里
actually within their bodies.

300
0:47:25,800 --> 0:47:28,800
俪虾让菌群寄居在他们的口腔
Shrimps carry such cultures in their mouthparts,

301
0:47:29,960 --> 0:47:32,440
但这也是一个十分危险的办法
but that is a strategy fraught with danger.

302
0:47:37,160 --> 0:47:40,880
因为俪虾需要冒着随时被煮熟的危险
To provide sustenance for these microbes

303
0:47:40,880 --> 0:47:44,440
冲进热水喷泉中
the shrimps must dash into the hot vents...

304
0:47:46,360 --> 0:47:49,160
只为更好地为这些微生物提供食物
..And that risks being boiled alive.

305
0:48:02,960 --> 0:48:04,880
过去十年间
In the last decade

306
0:48:04,880 --> 0:48:08,440
人们发现的海底喷泉数量翻了一番
the number of hydrothermal vents discovered has doubled.

307
0:48:16,400 --> 0:48:20,080
每一个喷泉都有它独立的生物群落
Every one has its own unique character and community.

308
0:48:27,180 --> 0:48:31,320
但其中最重要的 应该是一座位于大西洋的海底喷泉 
But perhaps the most important one of all is in the Atlantic.

309
0:48:32,640 --> 0:48:36,220
名曰 失落之城
It has been named "The Lost City".

310
0:48:39,600 --> 0:48:42,360
在它那高达60米的矿物塔里
Within its 60-metre towers,

311
0:48:42,360 --> 0:48:45,770
上演着各种不可思议的画面
something truly extraordinary is taking place.

312
0:48:49,480 --> 0:48:54,360
在这样一个极端的高温高压环境里
Under extremes of pressure and temperature, hydrocarbons -

313
0:48:54,360 --> 0:48:59,360
不间断地生成生命的基本组成分子
the molecules that are the basic component of all living things -

314
0:48:59,360 --> 0:49:02,440
碳氢化合物
are being created spontaneously.

315
0:49:14,040 --> 0:49:17,200
事实上 许多科学家开始相信
Indeed, many scientists now believe

316
0:49:17,200 --> 0:49:19,920
40亿年前 地球上最初的生命
that life on Earth may have begun

317
0:49:19,920 --> 0:49:22,640
很可能就起源于
around a vent like this,

318
0:49:22,640 --> 0:49:25,400
类似的海底喷泉
four billion years ago.

319
0:49:44,440 --> 0:49:50,920
我们现在了解到在木星和土星的卫星上也有这样的深海
We now know that there are deep seas on the moons of Jupiter and Saturn.

320
0:49:57,200 --> 0:49:58,720
如果地球上 
If life can exist

321
0:49:58,770 --> 0:50:01,880
如此极限环境里 都能有生物存在
under such extreme conditions down here,

322
0:50:01,880 --> 0:50:06,530
那么远在地球之外的某处也会有生命诞生
then surely it could exist somewhere out there.

323
0:50:31,480 --> 0:50:35,680
摄制组花了1000多小时潜入深海拍摄
The team spent more than 1,000 hours filming in the deep ocean,

324
0:50:35,680 --> 0:50:40,480
通常乘坐探险潜艇 阿卢西亚号 和她的姐妹潜艇
mostly from the research vessel Alucia and her twin submersibles,

325
0:50:40,480 --> 0:50:42,560
深海漫游者号 和  纳迪尔号
Deep Rover and Nadir.

326
0:50:47,960 --> 0:50:51,600
拍摄南极洲是最壮志豪情的一次任务
Their most ambitious mission was to Antarctica,

327
0:50:52,280 --> 0:50:55,280
摄制组希望在海底三分之二英尺下拍到生命
hoping to film life two thirds of a mile down,

328
0:50:55,280 --> 0:50:57,120
这在以前从未尝试过
something never attempted before.

329
0:51:02,640 --> 0:51:05,240
事实上我们不知道我们会发现什么
We honestly do not know what we're going to find down there.

330
0:51:05,240 --> 0:51:08,600
我们只是去探索人类从未涉足之地
We're going to a place that has never been explored.

331
0:51:08,600 --> 0:51:11,280
那里也许空空如也 也许生机勃勃
There could be nothing, there could be a carpet of life,

332
0:51:11,280 --> 0:51:14,120
或者有意外之喜 谁知道呢
there could be anything in between. Who knows?

333
0:51:18,240 --> 0:51:20,480
这是一项艰难的技术挑战
It's a huge technical challenge.

334
0:51:27,600 --> 0:51:32,440
水温达到零下1.8摄氏度
The water temperature here can reach minus 1.8 Centigrade.

335
0:51:37,720 --> 0:51:40,520
没有人知道潜水艇在这样的
No-one knows for sure how the subs will cope

336
0:51:40,520 --> 0:51:42,360
恶劣环境下会怎样
with this extreme environment.

337
0:51:48,080 --> 0:51:51,440
好 行 我把渗的水吸干 好了
OK. Right, I'm going to soak it up. OK.

338
0:51:51,440 --> 0:51:54,360
第一次潜水半个小时后
Just half an hour into the very first dive,

339
0:51:54,360 --> 0:51:56,960
潜水艇里发现了一个水洼
a puddle is forming on the floor of the sub.

340
0:52:00,600 --> 0:52:02,600
奥尔拉确认它是渗进来的海水
Orla confirms it's seawater.

341
0:52:04,200 --> 0:52:08,200
好的 收到 我尝试把水吸干
Yeah, Roger. I'm just try to soak up this puddle of water,

342
0:52:08,200 --> 0:52:10,360
然后再看看是否还有进水
and then see if any more comes.

343
0:52:11,360 --> 0:52:15,120
他们必须很快找到裂缝 修好它
They must find the leak and repair it fast.

344
0:52:15,120 --> 0:52:17,640
- 需要我把椅子移一下吗 - 是的
- Are you going to knock that over my...? - Yeah.

345
0:52:17,640 --> 0:52:22,000
你坐在已下沉450米深的小潜艇里 然后它进水了
You're at 450 metres in a small bubble and water's coming in.

346
0:52:22,000 --> 0:52:25,720
回到海平面要花半个小时
That's a half an hour straight shot back up to the surface.

347
0:52:25,720 --> 0:52:27,680
就会开始想
You're kind of thinking about,

348
0:52:27,680 --> 0:52:29,500
是放弃还是继续下潜
"Are we going to fill up with water?

349
0:52:29,500 --> 0:52:31,280
如果继续下潜的话 就必死无疑了
And if we are, there's no way out!"

350
0:52:32,520 --> 0:52:34,080
是的
Yeah.

351
0:52:34,080 --> 0:52:37,160
潜艇驾驶员在这个时候处理得很冷静
The sub pilots are well drilled for emergencies.

352
0:52:39,880 --> 0:52:42,520
把那些东西清空 好的
Just pass them over. Yeah.

353
0:52:42,520 --> 0:52:45,480
拉尔夫很快找到了裂缝并修好它
Ralph quickly finds the flood and fixes it.

354
0:52:47,440 --> 0:52:50,680
整个过程他看起来不慌不忙
He made it all seem absolutely ordinary and normal and,

355
0:52:50,680 --> 0:52:53,080
我搞定它了 不要担心
"I've got this covered, don't you worry,"

356
0:52:53,080 --> 0:52:54,840
20分钟之内 他就搞定了
and within 20 minutes, he did.

357
0:53:00,360 --> 0:53:03,880
南极海峡多姿多彩
The waters of the Antarctic Sound are potentially rich

358
0:53:03,880 --> 0:53:05,640
也危机四伏
but also treacherous.

359
0:53:07,080 --> 0:53:11,280
比如著名的 艾利冰山
The Sound is ominously known as "Iceberg Alley".

360
0:53:12,960 --> 0:53:14,030
我们要找一个
We've got to find a place

361
0:53:14,030 --> 0:53:15,880
可以让潜水艇自由升降
where we can get the submarines down and up

362
0:53:15,880 --> 0:53:18,600
没有冰山碰撞和挡道的地方
safely without any icebergs coming along and bowling them over.

363
0:53:18,600 --> 0:53:20,000
我感觉
I've got a feeling it's going

364
0:53:20,000 --> 0:53:22,040
有点儿像太空侵略者游戏
to be a bit like a game of Space Invaders.

365
0:53:23,400 --> 0:53:25,920
一立方米冰块重达一吨
A metre cube of ice weighs a tonne.

366
0:53:25,980 --> 0:53:28,880
你似乎在小心翼翼地绕着一个球体碾磨
You start sort of grinding that around the sphere,

367
0:53:29,060 --> 0:53:29,930
感觉很奇妙
it's delicate.

368
0:53:30,000 --> 0:53:31,720
它就像一颗大彩蛋
It's like a big Faberge egg.

369
0:53:34,360 --> 0:53:36,020
有一次下潜刚刚好
One dive brings them right

370
0:53:36,020 --> 0:53:38,520
避过了潜艇顶上的冰山底
up to the underside face of an iceberg.

371
0:53:41,640 --> 0:53:45,120
一会儿有小汽车大小的冰山
There are icebergs up there that are the size of a small car, and

372
0:53:45,120 --> 0:53:49,480
一会儿又有海德公园一样的冰山
then there are icebergs up there that are the size of Hyde Park.

373
0:53:49,480 --> 0:53:50,880
庞然巨物
Enormous.

374
0:53:52,520 --> 0:53:55,080
这里的环境瞬息万变
Conditions here can change in an instant.

375
0:53:56,330 --> 0:53:58,890
船长向潜艇发送无线电信息
The captain radios down to the subs

376
0:54:03,000 --> 0:54:03,720
是 收到
Yeah, Roger that.

377
0:54:05,600 --> 0:54:08,760
我们突然发现有两座冰山从冰架上崩落下来
We've currently got a couple of big icebergs coming down the channel,

378
0:54:08,820 --> 0:54:11,600
而且它们似乎就快撞到一起了
and it looks like they're on a collision course.

379
0:54:14,920 --> 0:54:19,200
两座冰山相撞的声音就在上方
The impact of two icebergs colliding overhead is clearly heard.

380
0:54:22,560 --> 0:54:24,040
那就是冰山
That is ice.

381
0:54:26,520 --> 0:54:30,200
冰山相撞的同时天气也变得糟糕
With icebergs colliding above and the weather turning fast,

382
0:54:30,200 --> 0:54:32,080
潜艇很快被召回
the subs are quickly recalled.

383
0:54:39,480 --> 0:54:41,600
摄制再次半途而废
Once again their efforts are thwarted.

384
0:54:52,680 --> 0:54:56,440
终于 两周之后 天气变得晴好
Finally, after two weeks, conditions are just right.

385
0:54:57,560 --> 0:55:02,620
摄制组又开始了深潜艾利冰山千米以下的探险
Once again the team attempt their 1,000-metre dive in Iceberg Alley.

386
0:55:06,200 --> 0:55:09,840
下潜一个小时之后 他们才接近目标
An hour after leaving the surface they close in on their goal.

387
0:55:13,880 --> 0:55:15,320
999
999.

388
0:55:19,240 --> 0:55:20,620
控制中心 控制中心
Control, control.

389
0:55:20,620 --> 0:55:22,560
纳蒂亚号
This is Nadir

390
0:55:22,560 --> 0:55:27,560
到达底部 深度 1000米
on bottom, depth - one-zero-zero-zero metres.

391
0:55:27,560 --> 0:55:29,680
收到 深度 1000米
Roger. Depth - 1,000 metres.

392
0:55:29,680 --> 0:55:31,880
暂停 新纪录
Control out. New record!

393
0:55:34,160 --> 0:55:37,800
人类第一次在南极洲深潜达1000米
First manned sub dive to 1,000 metres in Antarctica!

394
0:55:39,840 --> 0:55:42,760
在深海底部 世界的尽头
At the bottom of the ocean, at the end of the world,

395
0:55:42,760 --> 0:55:45,720
他们惊喜地发现了数以万计的生物群
the amount of life they find is astonishing.

396
0:55:51,480 --> 0:55:54,440
他们同时震惊地发现
But they are equally astonished to find that,

397
0:55:54,440 --> 0:55:56,840
离水面三分之二英里的地方
two thirds of a mile from the surface,

398
0:55:56,840 --> 0:55:58,760
冰山仍具危险性
icebergs are still a danger.

399
0:56:00,760 --> 0:56:03,640
石块因为冰山融化而掉进海里
Rocks can drop from them as they melt,

400
0:56:03,640 --> 0:56:06,640
其中一块差点就砸到潜水艇上
and one lands right in front of the sub.

401
0:56:09,280 --> 0:56:12,440
我想大多数潜水的人
I don't think many people who are diving subs

402
0:56:12,440 --> 0:56:15,880
压根不会考虑被石块击中这种事
ever consider big lumps of rock landing on them.

403
0:56:16,620 --> 0:56:19,320
这不是常见的风险项
It's, it's not your normal risk.

404
0:56:19,320 --> 0:56:20,800
如果潜艇被这小石块击中
If it had hit the sphere,

405
0:56:20,800 --> 0:56:23,800
顶多也就被稍微刮花一点
there's a good chance it would have put a nice scratch down it.

406
0:56:23,800 --> 0:56:27,160
但如果这个石块是10到20吨重
If something of ten, 15, 20 tonnes had hit the sub,

407
0:56:27,160 --> 0:56:28,800
那么潜水艇就毁了
it would completely destroy it.

408
0:56:33,080 --> 0:56:35,160
但随着更深入的探索
But over the following dives

409
0:56:35,160 --> 0:56:37,840
摄制组发现 也正是这些落石
the team learns it's these very drop stones

410
0:56:37,860 --> 0:56:41,000
丰富了南极海底的生物群落
that enrich the Antarctic deep sea bed,

411
0:56:42,160 --> 0:56:45,720
提供了生命所需的栖息之所
creating firm anchor points for life to thrive.

412
0:56:50,400 --> 0:56:55,890
事实证明 想要欣赏海底深处繁盛的生命
Proof that the only way to fully appreciate the complexity and abundance of life in the deep

413
0:56:56,200 --> 0:56:58,400
需要我们亲自去探索
is to go there ourselves.

414
0:57:06,920 --> 0:57:10,480
下一次 我们去看看珊瑚礁
Next time, we travel to bustling coral reefs.

415
0:57:16,920 --> 0:57:21,240
在这里 海底动物们则需要长途跋涉
Here, animals must go to extraordinary lengths

416
0:57:21,240 --> 0:57:25,770
只为在这拥挤的空间里生存
to get ahead of the competition in these crowded cities.

